  "prompt": "What were the terms to the Treaty of Versailles?",
  "response": "The Treaty of Versailles, signed on June 28, 1919, after World War I, imposed harsh penalties on Germany. Key terms included:\n\n1. War Guilt Clause\n- Germany accepted full responsibility for starting World War I\n- Blamed for all war damages\n\n2. Military Restrictions\n- German army limited to 100,000 men\n- Prohibited from having submarines or an air force\n- Demilitarization of the Rhineland\n\n3. Territorial Losses\n- Germany lost about 13% of its European territory\n- Alsace-Lorraine returned to France\n- Parts of Prussia given to Poland\n- All overseas colonies were seized\n\n4. Reparations\n- Germany required to pay massive war reparations\n- Initially set at 132 billion gold marks (approximately $33 billion)\n- Intended to cover civilian damage caused during the war\n\n5. Economic Consequences\n- Significant economic restrictions\n- Loss of important industrial regions\n- Severe economic penalties\n\n6. League of Nations\n- Germany was initially excluded from the League of Nations\n- Forced to accept the treaty's terms\n\nThese terms were considered extremely punitive and contributed to economic hardship and political resentment in Germany, which many historians believe helped set the stage for World War II.",
